                    "id": "sec3",
                    "title": "Finite element discretization"
                }
            ],
            "secId": "sec3.3",
            "sentence": "When the beam is embedded in a plate, which is the case in this work, the need for the stabilization term is mitigated, and if the plate is sufficiently stiff we may omit the stabilization term, see Section 3.5 for further details.",
            "startOffset": 125628,
            "title": "The cut c/dG method for a beam"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 111582,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "sec1",
            "sentence": "Reinforcements of plates using lower\u2013dimensional structures such as beams are often employed for the purpose of increasing buckling loads and avoiding eigenfrequencies in vibration problems.",
            "startOffset": 111392,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 119489,
            "parents": [
                {
                    "id": "sec2",
                    "title": "Modeling of reinforced plates"
                }
            ],
            "secId": "sec2.3",
            "sentence": "If the beams are located on one side of the plate the main approach is the same but we must include models for the membrane deformation of the plate and beams.",
            "startOffset": 119330,
            "title": "The Euler\u2013Bernoulli beam model"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 125627,
            "parents": [
                {
                    "id": "sec3",
                    "title": "Finite element discretization"
                }
            ],
            "refoffsets": {
