                },
                "bib2": {
                    "endOffset": 125625,
                    "startOffset": 125624
                }
            },
            "secId": "sec3.3",
            "sentence": "The basic principle is the same as for the trace finite element method proposed in Ref. [18] and the stabilized version proposed in Ref. [2].",
            "startOffset": 125486,
            "title": "The cut c/dG method for a beam"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 114107,
            "parents": [
                {
                    "id": "sec2",
                    "title": "Modeling of reinforced plates"
                }
            ],
            "secId": "sec2.1",
            "sentence": "To ensure coercivity of the cut beam model we in general need to add a certain stabilization term which provides control of the discrete functions variation in the vicinity of the beam.",
            "startOffset": 113922,
            "title": "The basic approach"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 111810,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "sec1",
            "sentence": "Different approaches have been suggested:",
            "startOffset": 111769,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 114322,
            "parents": [
                {
                    "id": "sec2",
                    "title": "Modeling of reinforced plates"
                }
            ],
            "refoffsets": {
                "bib1": {
                    "endOffset": 114305,
                    "startOffset": 114304
                }
            },
            "secId": "sec2.1",
            "sentence": "However, for beams embedded in a plate, the plate stabilizes the beam discretizations, and we shall show that if the plate is stiff enough compared to the beam the usual additional stabilization [1] is superfluous.",
            "startOffset": 114108,
            "title": "The basic approach"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 113738,
            "parents": [
                {
                    "id": "sec2",
                    "title": "Modeling of reinforced plates"
                }
            ],
            "secId": "sec2.1",
            "sentence": "To formulate a finite element method on the restricted or trace finite element space we employ continuous/discontinuous Galerkin approximations of the Euler\u2013Bernoulli beam model.",
            "startOffset": 113560,
            "title": "The basic approach"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 132677,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "sec5",
            "sentence": "The method has the advantage that we can discretize both the beam and plate problem with the same standard finite element spaces of continuous piecewise polynomials defined on triangles (or quadrilaterals).",
            "startOffset": 132471,
            "title": "Conclusions"
        },
        {
