            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "bib12": {
                    "endOffset": 112829,
                    "startOffset": 112827
                }
            },
            "secId": "sec1",
            "sentence": "In Ref. [12] we proposed to use the same finite element space for the beam as for the higher dimensional structure modeled by linear elasticity, using second order polynomials for elasticity and taking the restriction, or trace, of these polynomials to model the beam using c/dG.",
            "startOffset": 112818,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 113922,
            "parents": [
                {
                    "id": "sec2",
                    "title": "Modeling of reinforced plates"
                }
            ],
            "secId": "sec2.1",
            "sentence": "The beams are then modeled using the CutFEM paradigm and the stiffness of the embedded beams is in the most basic version, which we consider here, simply added to the plate stiffness.",
            "startOffset": 113739,
            "title": "The basic approach"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 119329,
            "parents": [
                {
                    "id": "sec2",
                    "title": "Modeling of reinforced plates"
                }
            ],
            "secId": "sec2.3",
            "sentence": "We assume that the beam centerline is located in the symmetry plane of the plate, see Fig. 2, which simplifies the modeling of a reinforced plate since it will be subject to pure bending.",
